  "prompt": "When do the rabies symptoms occur in humans?",
  "response": "Rabies symptoms in humans typically occur after an incubation period, which can range from a few weeks to several months, and rarely up to a year or more. The incubation period is the time between the initial exposure to the rabies virus (usually through a bite or scratch from an infected animal) and the onset of symptoms. \n\nThe timing of symptom onset depends on several factors, including:\n\n1. **Location of the bite**: Bites closer to the central nervous system (e.g., the head, neck, or face) may result in a shorter incubation period.\n2. **Severity of the exposure**: A deeper or more severe bite may lead to a faster onset of symptoms.\n3. **Amount of virus introduced**: A higher viral load may shorten the incubation period.\n\n### Stages of Rabies Symptoms:\nOnce symptoms begin, rabies typically progresses through the following stages:\n\n1. **Prodromal Stage (2-10 days)**:\n   - Non-specific symptoms resembling the flu, such as fever, headache, fatigue, and discomfort at the site of the bite.\n   - Tingling, itching, or pain at the wound site.\n\n2. **Acute Neurological Stage**:\n   - **Furious Rabies**: Hyperactivity, agitation, hallucinations, hydrophobia (fear of water), aerophobia (fear of air or drafts), and difficulty swallowing.\n   - **Paralytic Rabies**: Muscle weakness, paralysis, and a more subdued progression of the disease.\n\n3. **Coma and Death**:\n   - Without prompt treatment, rabies is nearly always fatal once symptoms appear. Death usually occurs within a few days to weeks after the onset of symptoms.\n\n### Critical Notes:\n- **Prevention is key**: If you are bitten or scratched by a potentially rabid animal, seek medical attention immediately. Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP), which includes rabies vaccination and immunoglobulin, can prevent the disease if administered early.\n- **Symptoms are a medical emergency**: Once symptoms of rabies appear, the disease is almost universally fatal. Early intervention is critical. \n\nAlways consult a healthcare professional for guidance if you suspect exposure to rabies.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
